# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: counting-bloom-filter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] In computing, a **Bloom filter** is a space-efficient probabilistic data structure, conceived by Burton Howard Bloom in 1970, that is used to test whether an element is a member of a set.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] False positive matches are possible, but false negatives are not – in other words, a query returns either "possibly in set" or "definitely not in set".
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Elements can be added to the set, but not removed (though this can be addressed with the counting Bloom filter variant); the more items added, the larger the probability of false positives.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Bloom proposed the technique for applications where the amount of source data would require an impractically large amount of memory if "conventional" error-free hashing techniques were applied.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] He gave the example of a hyphenation algorithm for a dictionary of 500,000 words, out of which 90% follow simple hyphenation rules, but the remaining 10% require expensive disk accesses to retrieve specific hyphenation patterns.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] With sufficient core memory, an error-free hash could be used to eliminate all unnecessary disk accesses; on the other hand, with limited core memory, Bloom's technique uses a smaller hash area but still eliminates most unnecessary accesses.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] For example, a hash area only 18% of the size needed by an ideal error-free hash still eliminates 87% of the disk accesses.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] More generally, fewer than 10 bits per element are required for a 1% false positive probability, independent of the size or number of elements in the set.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] An *empty Bloom filter* is a bit array of m bits, all set to 0.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] It is equipped with k different hash functions, which map set elements to one of the m possible array positions.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] To be optimal, the hash functions should be uniformly distributed and independent.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Typically, k is a small constant which depends on the desired false error rate ε, while m is proportional to k and the number of elements to be added.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] To *add* an element, feed it to each of the k hash functions to get k array positions.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Set the bits at all these positions to 1.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] To *test* whether an element is in the set, feed it to each of the k hash functions to get k array positions.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] If *any* of the bits at these positions is 0, the element is definitely not in the set; if it were, then all the bits would have been set to 1 when it was inserted.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] If all are 1, then either the element is in the set, *or* the bits have by chance been set to 1 during the insertion of other elements, resulting in a false positive.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] In a simple Bloom filter, there is no way to distinguish between the two cases, but more advanced techniques can address this problem.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The requirement of designing k different independent hash functions can be prohibitive for large k.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] For a good hash function with a wide output, there should be little if any correlation between different bit-fields of such a hash, so this type of hash can be used to generate multiple "different" hash functions by slicing its output into multiple bit fields.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Alternatively, one can pass k different initial values (such as 0, 1, ..., k − 1) to a hash function that takes an initial value; or add (or append) these values to the key.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] For larger m and/or k, independence among the hash functions can be relaxed with negligible increase in false positive rate.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Removing an element from this simple Bloom filter is impossible because there is no way to tell which of the k bits it maps to should be cleared.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Although setting any one of those k bits to zero suffices to remove the element, it would also remove any other elements that happen to map onto that bit.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Since the simple algorithm provides no way to determine whether any other elements have been added that affect the bits for the element to be removed, clearing any of the bits would introduce the possibility of false negatives.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] One-time removal of an element from a Bloom filter can be simulated by having a second Bloom filter that contains items that have been removed.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] However, false positives in the second filter become false negatives in the composite filter, which may be undesirable.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] In this approach re-adding a previously removed item is not possible, as one would have to remove it from the "removed" filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] It is often the case that all the keys are available but are expensive to enumerate (for example, requiring many disk reads).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] When the false positive rate gets too high, the filter can be regenerated; this should be a relatively rare event.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] While risking false positives, Bloom filters have a substantial space advantage over other data structures for representing sets, such as self-balancing binary search trees, tries, hash tables, or simple arrays or linked lists of the entries.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Most of these require storing at least the data items themselves, which can require anywhere from a small number of bits, for small integers, to an arbitrary number of bits, such as for strings (tries are an exception since they can share storage between elements with equal prefixes).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] However, Bloom filters do not store the data items at all, and a separate solution must be provided for the actual storage.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Linked structures incur an additional linear space overhead for pointers.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] A Bloom filter with a 1% error and an optimal value of k, in contrast, requires only about 9.6 bits per element, regardless of the size of the elements.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] This advantage comes partly from its compactness, inherited from arrays, and partly from its probabilistic nature.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The 1% false-positive rate can be reduced by a factor of ten by adding only about 4.8 bits per element.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] However, if the number of potential values is small and many of them can be in the set, the Bloom filter is easily surpassed by the deterministic bit array, which requires only one bit for each potential element.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Hash tables gain a space and time advantage if they begin ignoring collisions and store only whether each bucket contains an entry; in this case, they have effectively become Bloom filters with *k* = 1.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Bloom filters also have the unusual property that the time needed either to add items or to check whether an item is in the set is a fixed constant, O(*k*), completely independent of the number of items already in the set.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] No other constant-space set data structure has this property, but the average access time of sparse hash tables can make them faster in practice than some Bloom filters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] In a hardware implementation, however, the Bloom filter shines because its k lookups are independent and can be parallelized.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] To understand its space efficiency, it is instructive to compare the general Bloom filter with its special case when *k* = 1.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] If *k* = 1, then in order to keep the false positive rate sufficiently low, a small fraction of bits should be set, which means the array must be very large and contain long runs of zeros.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The information content of the array relative to its size is low.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Assume that a hash function selects each array position with equal probability.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Now test membership of an element that is not in the set.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Each of the *k* array positions computed by the hash functions is 1 with a probability as above.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] This is not strictly correct as it assumes independence for the probabilities of each bit being set.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] However, assuming it is a close approximation we have that the probability of false positives decreases as *m* (the number of bits in the array) increases, and increases as *n* (the number of inserted elements) increases.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] where the {braces} denote Stirling numbers of the second kind.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] An alternative analysis arriving at the same approximation without the assumption of independence is given by Mitzenmacher and Upfal.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] After all *n* items have been added to the Bloom filter, let *q* be the fraction of the *m* bits that are set to 0.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] (That is, the number of bits still set to 0 is *qm*.) Then, when testing membership of an element not in the set, for the array position given by any of the *k* hash functions, the probability that the bit is found set to 1 is $1-q$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] So the probability that all *k* hash functions find their bit set to 1 is $(1-q)^{k}$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] It is possible to prove, without the independence assumption, that *q* is very strongly concentrated around its expected value.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The number of hash functions, *k*, must be a positive integer.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] This means that for a given false positive probability *ε*, the length of a Bloom filter *m* is proportionate to the number of elements being filtered *n* and the required number of hash functions only depends on the target false positive probability *ε*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The formula $m=-{\frac {n\ln \varepsilon }{(\ln 2)^{2}}}$ is approximate for three reasons.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] First, and of least concern, it approximates $1-{\frac {1}{m}}$ as $e^{-{\frac {1}{m}}}$ , which is a good asymptotic approximation (i.e., which holds as *m* →∞).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Second, of more concern, it assumes that during the membership test the event that one tested bit is set to 1 is independent of the event that any other tested bit is set to 1.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Third, of most concern, it assumes that $k={\frac {m}{n}}\ln 2$ is fortuitously integral.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Goel and Gupta, however, give a rigorous upper bound that makes no approximations and requires no assumptions.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] This bound can be interpreted as saying that the approximate formula $\left(1-e^{-{\frac {kn}{m}}}\right)^{k}$ can be applied at a penalty of at most half an extra element and at most one less bit.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] where *$n^{*}$* is an estimate of the number of items in the filter, *m* is the length (size) of the filter, *k* is the number of hash functions, and *X* is the number of bits set to one.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Bloom filters are a way of compactly representing a set of items.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] It is common to try to compute the size of the intersection or union between two sets.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Bloom filters can be used to approximate the size of the intersection and union of two sets.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] where $n(A\cup B)$ is the number of bits set to one in either of the two Bloom filters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Classic Bloom filters use $1.44\log _{2}(1/\varepsilon )$ bits of space per inserted key, where $\varepsilon$ is the false positive rate of the Bloom filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] However, the space that is strictly necessary for any data structure playing the same role as a Bloom filter is only $\log _{2}(1/\varepsilon )$ per key.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Hence Bloom filters use 44% more space than an equivalent optimal data structure.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Pagh et al. provide a data structure that uses ${\textstyle (1+o(1))n\log _{2}(1/\epsilon )+O(n)}$ bits while supporting constant amortized expected-time operations.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Their data structure is primarily theoretical, but it is closely related to the widely-used quotient filter, which can be parameterized to use $(1+\delta )n\log \epsilon ^{-1}+3n$ bits of space, for an arbitrary parameter $\delta >0$ , while supporting $O(\delta ^{-2})$ -time operations.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Advantages of the quotient filter, when compared to the Bloom filter, include its locality of reference and the ability to support deletions.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Another alternative to classic Bloom filter is the cuckoo filter, based on space-efficient variants of cuckoo hashing.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] In this case, a hash table is constructed, holding neither keys nor values, but short fingerprints (small hashes) of the keys.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] If looking up the key finds a matching fingerprint, then key is probably in the set.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Cuckoo filters support deletions and have better locality of reference than Bloom filters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Additionally, in some parameter regimes, cuckoo filters can be parameterized to offer nearly optimal space guarantees.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Many alternatives to Bloom filters, including quotient filters and cuckoo filters, are based on the idea of hashing keys to random $(\log n+\log \epsilon ^{-1})$ -bit fingerprints, and then storing those fingerprints in a compact hash table.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] This technique, which was first introduced by Carter et al. in 1978, relies on the fact that compact hash tables can be implemented to use roughly $n\log n$ bits less space than their non-compact counterparts.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Using succinct hash tables, the space usage can be reduced to as little as $n\log _{2}(e/\epsilon )+o(n)$ bits while supporting constant-time operations in a wide variety of parameter regimes.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Putze, Sanders & Singler (2007) have studied some variants of Bloom filters that are either faster or use less space than classic Bloom filters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The basic idea of the fast variant is to locate the k hash values associated with each key into one or two blocks having the same size as processor's memory cache blocks (usually 64 bytes).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] This will presumably improve performance by reducing the number of potential memory cache misses.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The proposed variants have however the drawback of using about 32% more space than classic Bloom filters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The space efficient variant relies on using a single hash function that generates for each key a value in the range $\left[0,n/\varepsilon \right]$ where $\varepsilon$ is the requested false positive rate.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The sequence of values is then sorted and compressed using Golomb coding (or some other compression technique) to occupy a space close to $n\log _{2}(1/\varepsilon )$ bits.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] To query the Bloom filter for a given key, it will suffice to check if its corresponding value is stored in the Bloom filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Decompressing the whole Bloom filter for each query would make this variant totally unusable.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] To overcome this problem the sequence of values is divided into small blocks of equal size that are compressed separately.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] At query time only half a block will need to be decompressed on average.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Because of decompression overhead, this variant may be slower than classic Bloom filters but this may be compensated by the fact that a single hash function needs to be computed.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Graf & Lemire (2020) describes an approach called an *xor filter*, where they store fingerprints in a particular type of perfect hash table, producing a filter which is more memory efficient ( $1.23\log _{2}(1/\varepsilon )$ bits per key) and faster than Bloom or cuckoo filters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] (The time saving comes from the fact that a lookup requires exactly three memory accesses, which can all execute in parallel.) However, filter creation is more complex than Bloom and cuckoo filters, and it is not possible to modify the set after creation.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] There are over 60 variants of Bloom filters, many surveys of the field, and a continuing churn of applications (see e.g., Luo, *et al* ).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Some of the variants differ sufficiently from the original proposal to be breaches from or forks of the original data structure and its philosophy.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] A treatment which unifies Bloom filters with other work on random projections, compressive sensing, and locality sensitive hashing remains to be done (though see Dasgupta, *et al* for one attempt inspired by neuroscience).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Content delivery networks deploy web caches around the world to cache and serve web content to users with greater performance and reliability.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] A key application of Bloom filters is their use in efficiently determining which web objects to store in these web caches.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Nearly three-quarters of the URLs accessed from a typical web cache are "one-hit-wonders" that are accessed by users only once and never again.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] It is clearly wasteful of disk resources to store one-hit-wonders in a web cache, since they will never be accessed again.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] To prevent caching one-hit-wonders, a Bloom filter is used to keep track of all URLs that are accessed by users.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] A web object is cached only when it has been accessed at least once before, i.e., the object is cached on its second request.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The use of a Bloom filter in this fashion significantly reduces the disk write workload, since most one-hit-wonders are not written to the disk cache.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Further, filtering out the one-hit-wonders also saves cache space on disk, increasing the cache hit rates.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Kiss *et al* described a new construction for the Bloom filter that avoids false positives in addition to the typical non-existence of false negatives.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The construction applies to a finite universe from which set elements are taken.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] It relies on existing non-adaptive combinatorial group testing scheme by Eppstein, Goodrich and Hirschberg.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Unlike the typical Bloom filter, elements are hashed to a bit array through deterministic, fast and simple-to-calculate functions.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The maximal set size for which false positives are completely avoided is a function of the universe size and is controlled by the amount of allocated memory.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] As the universe is finite and the set of false positives strictly shrinks with each step, this procedure results in a finite *cascade* of Bloom filters that (on this closed, finite domain) will produce only true positives and true negatives.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] To check for membership in the filter cascade, the initial filter is queried, and, if the result is positive, the second filter is then consulted, and so on.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] This construction is used in CRLite, a proposed certificate revocation status distribution mechanism for the Web PKI, and Certificate Transparency is exploited to close the set of extant certificates.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Counting filters provide a way to implement a *delete* operation on a Bloom filter without recreating the filter afresh.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] In a counting filter, the array positions (buckets) are extended from being a single bit to being a multibit counter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] In fact, regular Bloom filters can be considered as counting filters with a bucket size of one bit.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Counting filters were introduced by Fan et al.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The insert operation is extended to *increment* the value of the buckets, and the lookup operation checks that each of the required buckets is non-zero.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The delete operation then consists of decrementing the value of each of the respective buckets.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Arithmetic overflow of the buckets is a problem and the buckets should be sufficiently large to make this case rare.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] If it does occur then the increment and decrement operations must leave the bucket set to the maximum possible value in order to retain the properties of a Bloom filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The size of counters is usually 3 or 4 bits.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Hence counting Bloom filters use 3 to 4 times more space than static Bloom filters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] In contrast, the data structures of Pagh, Pagh & Rao (2005) and Fan et al.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] (2014) also allow deletions but use less space than a static Bloom filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Another issue with counting filters is limited scalability.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Because the counting Bloom filter table cannot be expanded, the maximal number of keys to be stored simultaneously in the filter must be known in advance.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Once the designed capacity of the table is exceeded, the false positive rate will grow rapidly as more keys are inserted.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] (2006) introduced a data structure based on d-left hashing that is functionally equivalent but uses approximately half as much space as counting Bloom filters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The scalability issue does not occur in this data structure.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Once the designed capacity is exceeded, the keys could be reinserted in a new hash table of double size.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The space efficient variant by Putze, Sanders & Singler (2007) could also be used to implement counting filters by supporting insertions and deletions.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Rottenstreich, Kanizo & Keslassy (2012) introduced a new general method based on variable increments that significantly improves the false positive probability of counting Bloom filters and their variants, while still supporting deletions.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Unlike counting Bloom filters, at each element insertion, the hashed counters are incremented by a hashed variable increment instead of a unit increment.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] To query an element, the exact values of the counters are considered and not just their positiveness.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] If a sum represented by a counter value cannot be composed of the corresponding variable increment for the queried element, a negative answer can be returned to the query.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] (2019) shows that false positive of Counting Bloom filter decreases from k=1 to a point defined $k_{opt}$ , and increases from $k_{opt}$ to positive infinity, and finds $k_{opt}$ as a function of count threshold.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Bloom filters can be organized in distributed data structures to perform fully decentralized computations of aggregate functions.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Decentralized aggregation makes collective measurements locally available in every node of a distributed network without involving a centralized computational entity for this purpose.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Parallel Bloom filters can be implemented to take advantage of the multiple processing elements (PEs) present in parallel shared-nothing machines.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] One of the main obstacles for a parallel Bloom filter is the organization and communication of the unordered data which is, in general, distributed evenly over all PEs at the initiation or at batch insertions.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] To order the data two approaches can be used, either resulting in a Bloom filter over all data being stored on each PE, called replicating bloom filter, or the Bloom filter over all data being split into equal parts, each PE storing one part of it.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] For both approaches a "Single Shot" Bloom filter is used which only calculates one hash, resulting in one flipped bit per element, to reduce the communication volume.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] During the communication of the hashes the PEs search for bits that are set in more than one of the receiving packets, as this would mean that two elements had the same hash and therefore could be duplicates.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] If this occurs a message containing the index of the bit, which is also the hash of the element that could be a duplicate, is sent to the PEs which sent a packet with the set bit.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] If multiple indices are sent to the same PE by one sender it can be advantageous to encode the indices as well.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] All elements that didn't have their hash sent back are now guaranteed to not be a duplicate and won't be evaluated further, for the remaining elements a Repartitioning algorithm can be used.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] First all the elements that had their hash value sent back are sent to the PE that their hash is responsible for.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Any element and its duplicate is now guaranteed to be on the same PE.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] In the second step each PE uses a sequential algorithm for duplicate detection on the receiving elements, which are only a fraction of the amount of starting elements.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] By allowing a false positive rate for the duplicates, the communication volume can be reduced further as the PEs don't have to send elements with duplicated hashes at all and instead any element with a duplicated hash can simply be marked as a duplicate.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] As a result, the false positive rate for duplicate detection is the same as the false positive rate of the used bloom filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The process of filtering out the most 'unique' elements can also be repeated multiple times by changing the hash function in each filtering step.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] While using more than two repetitions can reduce the communication volume further if the number of duplicates in a set is small, the payoff for the additional complications is low.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Bloom filters can be used for approximate data synchronization as in Byers et al.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Counting Bloom filters can be used to approximate the number of differences between two sets and this approach is described in Agarwal & Trachtenberg (2006).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Bloom filters can be adapted to the context of streaming data.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Another solution is the Aging Bloom filter, that consists of two Bloom filter each occupying half the total available memory: when one filter is full, the second filter is erased and newer elements are then added to this newly empty filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] This result shows that for L big enough and n going to infinity, then the lower bound converges to $FP+FN=1$ , which is the characteristic relation of a random filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Hence, after enough insertions, and if the alphabet is too big to be stored in memory (which is assumed in the context of probabilistic filters), it is impossible for a filter to perform better than randomness.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] This result can be leveraged by only expecting a filter to operate on a sliding window rather than the whole stream.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] In this case, the exponent n in the formula above is replaced by w, which gives a formula that might deviate from 1, if w is not too small.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] (2004) designed a generalization of Bloom filters that could associate a value with each element that had been inserted, implementing an associative array.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Like Bloom filters, these structures achieve a small space overhead by accepting a small probability of false positives.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] In the case of "Bloomier filters", a *false positive* is defined as returning a result when the key is not in the map.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The map will never return the wrong value for a key that *is* in the map.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Boldi & Vigna (2005) proposed a lattice-based generalization of Bloom filters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] A **compact approximator** associates to each key an element of a lattice (the standard Bloom filters being the case of the Boolean two-element lattice).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Instead of a bit array, they have an array of lattice elements.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] When adding a new association between a key and an element of the lattice, they compute the maximum of the current contents of the *k* array locations associated to the key with the lattice element.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] When reading the value associated to a key, they compute the minimum of the values found in the *k* locations associated to the key.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The resulting value approximates from above the original value.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] This implementation used a separate array for each hash function.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] This method allows for parallel hash calculations for both insertions and inquiries.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] (2007) proposed a variant of Bloom filters that can adapt dynamically to the number of elements stored, while assuring a minimum false positive probability.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The technique is based on sequences of standard Bloom filters with increasing capacity and tighter false positive probabilities, so as to ensure that a maximum false positive probability can be set beforehand, regardless of the number of elements to be inserted.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Spatial Bloom filters (SBF) were originally proposed by Palmieri, Calderoni & Maio (2014) as a data structure designed to store location information, especially in the context of cryptographic protocols for location privacy.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] However, the main characteristic of SBFs is their ability to store **multiple sets** in a single data structure, which makes them suitable for a number of different application scenarios.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Membership of an element to a specific set can be queried, and the false positive probability depends on the set: the first sets to be entered into the filter during construction have higher false positive probabilities than sets entered at the end.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] This property allows a prioritization of the sets, where sets containing more "important" elements can be preserved.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] A layered Bloom filter consists of multiple Bloom filter layers.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Layered Bloom filters allow keeping track of how many times an item was added to the Bloom filter by checking how many layers contain the item.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] With a layered Bloom filter a check operation will normally return the deepest layer number the item was found in.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] An attenuated Bloom filter of depth D can be viewed as an array of D normal Bloom filters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] In the context of service discovery in a network, each node stores regular and attenuated Bloom filters locally.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The regular or local Bloom filter indicates which services are offered by the node itself.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The attenuated filter of level i indicates which services can be found on nodes that are i-hops away from the current node.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The i-th value is constructed by taking a union of local Bloom filters for nodes i-hops away from the node.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] For example, consider a small network, shown on the graph below.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Say we are searching for a service A whose id hashes to bits 0,1, and 3 (pattern 11010).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] First, we check whether service A is offered by n1 by checking its local filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Since the patterns don't match, we check the attenuated Bloom filter in order to determine which node should be the next hop.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] We see that n2 doesn't offer service A but lies on the path to nodes that do.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Hence, we move to n2 and repeat the same procedure.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] We quickly find that n3 offers the service, and hence the destination is located.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] By using attenuated Bloom filters consisting of multiple layers, services at more than one hop distance can be discovered while avoiding saturation of the Bloom filter by attenuating (shifting out) bits set by sources further away.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Bloom filters are often used to search large chemical structure databases (see chemical similarity).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] In the simplest case, the elements added to the filter (called a *fingerprint* in this field) are just the atomic numbers present in the molecule, or a hash based on the atomic number of each atom and the number and type of its bonds.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] More advanced filters also encode atom counts, larger substructure features like carboxyl groups, and graph properties like the number of rings.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] In hash-based fingerprints, a hash function based on atom and bond properties is used to turn a subgraph into a PRNG seed, and the first output values used to set bits in the Bloom filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Molecular fingerprints started in the late 1940s as way to search for chemical structures searched on punched cards.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] However, it wasn't until around 1990 that Daylight Chemical Information Systems, Inc. introduced a hash-based method to generate the bits, rather than use a precomputed table.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Unlike the dictionary approach, the hash method can assign bits for substructures which hadn't previously been seen.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] In the early 1990s, the term "fingerprint" was considered different from "structural keys", but the term has since grown to encompass most molecular characteristics which can be used for a similarity comparison, including structural keys, sparse count fingerprints, and 3D fingerprints.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Unlike Bloom filters, the Daylight hash method allows the number of bits assigned per feature to be a function of the feature size, but most implementations of Daylight-like fingerprints use a fixed number of bits per feature, which makes them a Bloom filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] The original Daylight fingerprints could be used for both similarity and screening purposes.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Many other fingerprint types, like the popular ECFP2, can be used for similarity but not for screening because they include local environmental characteristics that introduce false negatives when used as a screen.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/bloom-filter] Even if these are constructed with the same mechanism, these are not Bloom filters because they cannot be used to filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] A **counting Bloom filter** (**CBF**) or **spectral Bloom filter** is a probabilistic data structure that is used to test whether the number of occurrences of a given element in a sequence exceeds a given threshold.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] As a generalized form of the Bloom filter, false positive matches are possible, but false negatives are not – in other words, a query returns either "possibly bigger or equal than the threshold" or "definitely smaller than the threshold".
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] Most of the parameters are defined same with Bloom filter, such as *m, k. m* is the number of counters in counting Bloom filter, which is expansion of *m* bits in Bloom filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] An *empty counting Bloom filter* is a *m* counters, all set to 0.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] Similar to Bloom filter, there must also be *k* different hash functions defined, each of which maps or hashes some set element to one of the *m* counter array positions, generating a uniform random distribution.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] It is also similar that *k* is a constant, much smaller than *m*, which is proportional to the number of elements to be added.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] The main generalization of Bloom filter is adding an element.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] To *add* an element, feed it to each of the *k* hash functions to get *k* array positions and *increment* the counters 1 at all these positions.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] To *query* for an element with a threshold *θ* (test whether the count number of an element is smaller than *θ*), feed it to each of the *k* hash functions to get *k* counter positions.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] If any of the counters at these positions is less than *θ*, the count number of element is definitely less than *θ* – if it were more and equal, then all the corresponding counters would have been greater or equal to *θ*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] If all are greater or equal to *θ*, then either the count is really greater or equal to *θ*, or the counters have by chance been greater or equal to *θ*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] If all are greater or equal to θ even though the count is smaller than *θ*, this circumstance is defined as false positive.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] This also should be minimized like Bloom filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] About hashing problem and advantages, see Bloom filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] A counting Bloom filter is essentially the same data structure as count–min sketches, but are used differently.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] Several implementations of counting bloom filters allow for deletion, by decrementing each of the *k* counters for a given input.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] This will introduce the probability of false negatives during a query if the deleted input has not previously been inserted into the filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] Guo *et al.* present the problem in great detail, and provide heuristics for the parameters *m*, *k*, and *n* which minimize the probability of false negatives.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] The same assumptions in Bloom filter, which hash functions make insertions uniform random, is also assumed here.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] In the *m* pots, *kn* balls are inserted randomly.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] This is different from formal definition of false positive in counting Bloom filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] However, following the assumption in Bloom filter, above probability is defined as false positive of counting Bloom filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] If *θ*=1, the equation becomes false positive of Bloom filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] For large but fixed *n* and *m*, the false positive decreases from *k*=1 to a point defined $k_{opt}$ , and increases from $k_{opt}$ to positive infinity.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] (2019) shows numerical values of $k_{opt}$ within $1\leq \theta \leq 30$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] An invertible Bloom filter (IBF) is a variant of the counting Bloom filter that allows for listing of the remaining element, given there are not too may of them.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] There is, however, a small chance that multiple hash collisions can render a element unrecoverable.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] Like a CBF, an IBF consists of a hash table *B* which uses *k* hash functions *h*1...*h**k* and stores a counter in each of its *m* cells.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] Alongside each counter, it also stores a sum of elements and a sum of element hashes using a new hash function *g*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] There is also a second hash table *C* to recover elements that could not be recovered using *B*, which also has *m* cells but only uses two hash functions *f*1 and *f*2.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] The total number of elements (*n*) is also stored.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] Repeated insertions and removals can be simplified.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] A cell is considered "pure" if it contains only one distinct element *x*, which can be checked using `*g*(*B*[*i*].idSum/*B*[*i*].count) = *B*[*i*].hashSum/*B*[*i*].count`.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] If a cell is pure, then *x* can be recovered by dividing the idSum by the count.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] An invertible Bloom lookup table (IBLT) is a variant of the invertible Bloom filter that also stores associated values with each key.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] The difference is that an IBLT also stores a `valueSum` in each cell, which can be used to obtain the value for a given key.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] If there are no extraneous deletions (where a key is deleted without being inserted first) or duplicates (where a key is inserted multiple times), then the `hashkeySum` can be omitted.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] In this case, pure cells can be detected by checking whether `count = 1`.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] A `hashvalueSum` may also be stored in each cell to verify that only one value has been inserted for the corresponding key.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/counting-bloom-filter] IBLTs are suitable for use in databases, networking and compression.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] A **cuckoo filter** is a space-efficient probabilistic data structure that is used to test whether an element is a member of a set, like a Bloom filter does.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] A cuckoo filter can also delete existing items, which is not supported by Bloom filters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] In addition, for applications that store many items and target moderately low false positive rates, cuckoo filters can achieve lower space overhead than space-optimized Bloom filters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] Cuckoo filters were first described in 2014.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] A cuckoo filter uses a hash table based on cuckoo hashing to store the fingerprints of items.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] The data structure is broken into buckets of some size b .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] To insert the fingerprint of an item x , one first computes two potential buckets $h_{1}(x)$ and $h_{2}(x)$ where x could go.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] Note that, due to the symmetry of the XOR operation, one can compute $h_{2}(x)$ from $h_{1}(x)$ , and $h_{1}(x)$ from $h_{2}(x)$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] These properties are what make it possible to store the fingerprints with cuckoo hashing.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] The fingerprint of x is placed into one of buckets $h_{1}(x)$ and $h_{2}(x)$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] If the buckets are full, then one of the fingerprints in the bucket is evicted using cuckoo hashing, and placed into the other bucket where it can go.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] If that bucket, in turn, is also full, then that may trigger another eviction, etc.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] The hash table can achieve both high utilization (thanks to cuckoo hashing), and compactness because only fingerprints are stored.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] Lookup and delete operations of a cuckoo filter are straightforward.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] There are a maximum of two buckets to check by $h_{1}(x)$ and $h_{2}(x)$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] If found, the appropriate lookup or delete operation can be performed in $O(b)$ time.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] In order for the hash table to offer theoretical guarantees, the fingerprint size f must be at least $\Omega ((\log n)/b)$ bits.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/cuckoo-filter] Subject to this constraint, cuckoo filters guarantee a false-positive rate of at most $\epsilon \leq b/2^{f-1}$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A **hash function** is any function that can be used to map data of arbitrary size to fixed-size values, though there are some hash functions that support variable-length output.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The values returned by a hash function are called *hash values*, *hash codes*, (*hash/message*) *digests*, or simply *hashes*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The values are usually used to index a fixed-size table called a *hash table*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Use of a hash function to index a hash table is called *hashing* or *scatter-storage addressing*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Hash functions and their associated hash tables are used in data storage and retrieval applications to access data in a small and nearly constant time per retrieval.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] They require an amount of storage space only fractionally greater than the total space required for the data or records themselves.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Hashing is a way to access data quickly and efficiently.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Unlike lists or trees, it provides near-constant access time.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] It also uses much less storage than trying to store all possible keys directly, especially when keys are large or variable in length.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Use of hash functions relies on statistical properties of key and function interaction: worst-case behavior is intolerably bad but rare, and average-case behavior can be nearly optimal (minimal collision).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Hash functions are related to (and often confused with) checksums, check digits, fingerprints, lossy compression, randomization functions, error-correcting codes, and ciphers.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Although the concepts overlap to some extent, each one has its own uses and requirements and is designed and optimized differently.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The hash function differs from these concepts mainly in terms of data integrity.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Hash tables may use non-cryptographic hash functions, while cryptographic hash functions are used in cybersecurity to secure sensitive data such as passwords.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In a hash table, a hash function takes a key as an input, which is associated with a datum or record and used to identify it to the data storage and retrieval application.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The keys may be fixed-length, like an integer, or variable-length, like a name.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In some cases, the key is the datum itself.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The output is a hash code used to index a hash table holding the data or records, or pointers to them.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A good hash function satisfies two basic properties: it should be very fast to compute, and it should minimize duplication of output values (collisions).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Hash functions rely on generating favorable probability distributions for their effectiveness, reducing access time to nearly constant.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] High table loading factors, pathological key sets, and poorly designed hash functions can result in access times approaching linear in the number of items in the table.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Hash functions can be designed to give the best worst-case performance, good performance under high table loading factors, and in special cases, perfect (collisionless) mapping of keys into hash codes.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Implementation is based on parity-preserving bit operations (XOR and ADD), multiply, or divide.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A necessary adjunct to the hash function is a collision-resolution method that employs an auxiliary data structure like linked lists, or systematic probing of the table to find an empty slot.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Hash functions are used in conjunction with hash tables to store and retrieve data items or data records.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The hash function translates the key associated with each datum or record into a hash code, which is used to index the hash table.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] When an item is to be added to the table, the hash code may index an empty slot (also called a bucket), in which case the item is added to the table there.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] If the hash code indexes a full slot, then some kind of collision resolution is required: the new item may be omitted (not added to the table), or replace the old item, or be added to the table in some other location by a specified procedure.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] That procedure depends on the structure of the hash table.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In *chained hashing*, each slot is the head of a linked list or chain, and items that collide at the slot are added to the chain.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Chains may be kept in random order and searched linearly, or in serial order, or as a self-ordering list by frequency to speed up access.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In *open address hashing*, the table is probed starting from the occupied slot in a specified manner, usually by linear probing, quadratic probing, or double hashing until an open slot is located or the entire table is probed (overflow).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Searching for the item follows the same procedure until the item is located, an open slot is found, or the entire table has been searched (item not in table).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Hash functions are also used to build caches for large data sets stored in slow media.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A cache is generally simpler than a hashed search table, since any collision can be resolved by discarding or writing back the older of the two colliding items.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Hash functions are an essential ingredient of the Bloom filter, a space-efficient probabilistic data structure that is used to test whether an element is a member of a set.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A special case of hashing is known as geometric hashing or the *grid method*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In these applications, the set of all inputs is some sort of metric space, and the hashing function can be interpreted as a partition of that space into a grid of *cells*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The table is often an array with two or more indices (called a *grid file*, *grid index*, *bucket grid*, and similar names), and the hash function returns an index tuple.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Hash tables are also used to implement associative arrays and dynamic sets.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A good hash function should map the expected inputs as evenly as possible over its output range.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] That is, every hash value in the output range should be generated with roughly the same probability.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The reason for this requirement is that the cost of hashing-based methods goes up sharply as the number of *collisions* — pairs of inputs that are mapped to the same hash value — increases.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] If some hash values are more likely to occur than others, then a larger fraction of the lookup operations will have to search through a larger set of colliding table entries.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This criterion only requires the value to be *uniformly distributed*, not *random* in any sense.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A good randomizing function is (barring computational efficiency concerns) generally a good choice as a hash function, but the converse need not be true.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Hash tables often contain only a small subset of the valid inputs.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] For instance, a club membership list may contain only a hundred or so member names, out of the very large set of all possible names.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In these cases, the uniformity criterion should hold for almost all typical subsets of entries that may be found in the table, not just for the global set of all possible entries.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In other words, if a typical set of *m* records is hashed to *n* table slots, then the probability of a bucket receiving many more than *m*/*n* records should be vanishingly small.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In particular, if *m* < *n*, then very few buckets should have more than one or two records.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A small number of collisions is virtually inevitable, even if *n* is much larger than *m*—see the birthday problem.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In special cases when the keys are known in advance and the key set is static, a hash function can be found that achieves absolute (or collisionless) uniformity.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Such a hash function is said to be *perfect*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] There is no algorithmic way of constructing such a function—searching for one is a factorial function of the number of keys to be mapped versus the number of table slots that they are mapped into.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] When testing a hash function, the uniformity of the distribution of hash values can be evaluated by the chi-squared test.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This test is a goodness-of-fit measure: it is the actual distribution of items in buckets versus the expected (or uniform) distribution of items.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] where n is the number of keys, m is the number of buckets, and *b**j* is the number of items in bucket j.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A ratio within one confidence interval (such as 0.95 to 1.05) is indicative that the hash function evaluated has an expected uniform distribution.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Hash functions can have some technical properties that make it more likely that they will have a uniform distribution when applied.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] One is the strict avalanche criterion: whenever a single input bit is complemented, each of the output bits changes with a 50% probability.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The reason for this property is that selected subsets of the keyspace may have low variability.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] For the output to be uniformly distributed, a low amount of variability, even one bit, should translate into a high amount of variability (i.e. distribution over the tablespace) in the output.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Each bit should change with a probability of 50% because, if some bits are reluctant to change, then the keys become clustered around those values.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] If the bits want to change too readily, then the mapping is approaching a fixed XOR function of a single bit.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Standard tests for this property have been described in the literature.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The relevance of the criterion to a multiplicative hash function is assessed here.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In data storage and retrieval applications, the use of a hash function is a trade-off between search time and data storage space.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] If search time were unbounded, then a very compact unordered linear list would be the best medium; if storage space were unbounded, then a randomly accessible structure indexable by the key-value would be very large and very sparse, but very fast.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A hash function takes a finite amount of time to map a potentially large keyspace to a feasible amount of storage space searchable in a bounded amount of time regardless of the number of keys.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In most applications, the hash function should be computable with minimum latency and secondarily in a minimum number of instructions.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Computational complexity varies with the number of instructions required and latency of individual instructions, with the simplest being the bitwise methods (folding), followed by the multiplicative methods, and the most complex (slowest) are the division-based methods.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Because collisions should be infrequent, and cause a marginal delay but are otherwise harmless, it is usually preferable to choose a faster hash function over one that needs more computation but saves a few collisions.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Division-based implementations can be of particular concern because a division requires multiple cycles on nearly all processor microarchitectures.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Division (modulo) by a constant can be inverted to become a multiplication by the word-size multiplicative-inverse of that constant.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This can be done by the programmer, or by the compiler.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Division can also be reduced directly into a series of shift-subtracts and shift-adds, though minimizing the number of such operations required is a daunting problem; the number of machine-language instructions resulting may be more than a dozen and swamp the pipeline.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] If the microarchitecture has hardware multiply functional units, then the multiply-by-inverse is likely a better approach.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] We can allow the table size *n* to not be a power of 2 and still not have to perform any remainder or division operation, as these computations are sometimes costly.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] For example, let *n* be significantly less than 2*b*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Consider a pseudorandom number generator function *P*(key) that is uniform on the interval [0, 2*b* − 1].
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A hash function uniform on the interval [0, *n* − 1] is *n* *P*(key) / 2*b*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] We can replace the division by a (possibly faster) right bit shift: *n P*(key) >> *b*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] If keys are being hashed repeatedly, and the hash function is costly, then computing time can be saved by precomputing the hash codes and storing them with the keys.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Matching hash codes almost certainly means that the keys are identical.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This technique is used for the transposition table in game-playing programs, which stores a 64-bit hashed representation of the board position.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A *universal hashing* scheme is a randomized algorithm that selects a hash function *h* among a family of such functions, in such a way that the probability of a collision of any two distinct keys is 1/*m*, where *m* is the number of distinct hash values desired—independently of the two keys.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Universal hashing ensures (in a probabilistic sense) that the hash function application will behave as well as if it were using a random function, for any distribution of the input data.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] It will, however, have more collisions than perfect hashing and may require more operations than a special-purpose hash function.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A hash function that allows only certain table sizes or strings only up to a certain length, or cannot accept a seed (i.e. allow double hashing) is less useful than one that does.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A hash function is applicable in a variety of situations.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A hash procedure must be deterministic—for a given input value, it must always generate the same hash value.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In other words, it must be a function of the data to be hashed, in the mathematical sense of the term.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This requirement excludes hash functions that depend on external variable parameters, such as pseudo-random number generators or the time of day.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] It also excludes functions that depend on the memory address of the object being hashed, because the address may change during execution (as may happen on systems that use certain methods of garbage collection), although sometimes rehashing of the item is possible.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The determinism is in the context of the reuse of the function.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] For example, Python adds the feature that hash functions make use of a randomized seed that is generated once when the Python process starts in addition to the input to be hashed.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The Python hash (SipHash) is still a valid hash function when used within a single run, but if the values are persisted (for example, written to disk), they can no longer be treated as valid hash values, since in the next run the random value might differ.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] It is often desirable that the output of a hash function have fixed size (but see below).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] If, for example, the output is constrained to 32-bit integer values, then the hash values can be used to index into an array.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Such hashing is commonly used to accelerate data searches.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Producing fixed-length output from variable-length input can be accomplished by breaking the input data into chunks of specific size.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Hash functions used for data searches use some arithmetic expression that iteratively processes chunks of the input (such as the characters in a string) to produce the hash value.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In many applications, the range of hash values may be different for each run of the program or may change along the same run (for instance, when a hash table needs to be expanded).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In those situations, one needs a hash function which takes two parameters—the input data *z*, and the number *n* of allowed hash values.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A common solution is to compute a fixed hash function with a very large range (say, 0 to 232 − 1), divide the result by *n*, and use the division's remainder.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] If *n* is itself a power of 2, this can be done by bit masking and bit shifting.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] When this approach is used, the hash function must be chosen so that the result has fairly uniform distribution between 0 and *n* − 1, for any value of *n* that may occur in the application.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Depending on the function, the remainder may be uniform only for certain values of *n*, e.g. odd or prime numbers.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] When the hash function is used to store values in a hash table that outlives the run of the program, and the hash table needs to be expanded or shrunk, the hash table is referred to as a dynamic hash table.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A hash function that will relocate the minimum number of records when the table is resized is desirable.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] What is needed is a hash function *H*(*z*,*n*) (where *z* is the key being hashed and *n* is the number of allowed hash values) such that *H*(*z*,*n* + 1) = *H*(*z*,*n*) with probability close to *n*/(*n* + 1).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Linear hashing and spiral hashing are examples of dynamic hash functions that execute in constant time but relax the property of uniformity to achieve the minimal movement property.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Extendible hashing uses a dynamic hash function that requires space proportional to *n* to compute the hash function, and it becomes a function of the previous keys that have been inserted.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Several algorithms that preserve the uniformity property but require time proportional to *n* to compute the value of *H*(*z*,*n*) have been invented.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A hash function with minimal movement is especially useful in distributed hash tables.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In some applications, the input data may contain features that are irrelevant for comparison purposes.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] For example, when looking up a personal name, it may be desirable to ignore the distinction between upper and lower case letters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] For such data, one must use a hash function that is compatible with the data equivalence criterion being used: that is, any two inputs that are considered equivalent must yield the same hash value.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This can be accomplished by normalizing the input before hashing it, as by upper-casing all letters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] There are several common algorithms for hashing integers.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The method giving the best distribution is data-dependent.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] One of the simplest and most common methods in practice is the modulo division method.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] If the data to be hashed is small enough, then one can use the data itself (reinterpreted as an integer) as the hashed value.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The cost of computing this *identity* hash function is effectively zero.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This hash function is perfect, as it maps each input to a distinct hash value.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The meaning of "small enough" depends on the size of the type that is used as the hashed value.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] For example, in Java, the hash code is a 32-bit integer.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Thus the 32-bit integer `Integer` and 32-bit floating-point `Float` objects can simply use the value directly, whereas the 64-bit integer `Long` and 64-bit floating-point `Double` cannot.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Other types of data can also use this hashing scheme.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] For example, when mapping character strings between upper and lower case, one can use the binary encoding of each character, interpreted as an integer, to index a table that gives the alternative form of that character ("A" for "a", "8" for "8", etc.).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] If each character is stored in 8 bits (as in extended ASCII or ISO Latin 1), the table has only 28 = 256 entries; in the case of Unicode characters, the table would have 17 × 216 = 1114112 entries.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The same technique can be used to map two-letter country codes like "us" or "za" to country names (262 = 676 table entries), 5-digit ZIP codes like 13083 to city names (100000 entries), etc.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Invalid data values (such as the country code "xx" or the ZIP code 00000) may be left undefined in the table or mapped to some appropriate "null" value.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] If the keys are uniformly or sufficiently uniformly distributed over the key space, so that the key values are essentially random, then they may be considered to be already "hashed".
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In this case, any number of any bits in the key may be extracted and collated as an index into the hash table.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] For example, a simple hash function might mask off the m least significant bits and use the result as an index into a hash table of size 2*m*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A mid-squares hash code is produced by squaring the input and extracting an appropriate number of middle digits or bits.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] For example, if the input is 123456789 and the hash table size 10000, then squaring the key produces 15241578750190521, so the hash code is taken as the middle 4 digits of the 17-digit number (ignoring the high digit) 8750.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The mid-squares method produces a reasonable hash code if there is not a lot of leading or trailing zeros in the key.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This is a variant of multiplicative hashing, but not as good because an arbitrary key is not a good multiplier.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A standard technique is to use a modulo function on the key, by selecting a divisor M which is a prime number close to the table size, so *h*(*K*) ≡ *K* (mod *M*).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This gives a distribution from {0, *M* − 1}.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This gives good results over a large number of key sets.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A significant drawback of division hashing is that division requires multiple cycles on most modern architectures (including x86) and can be 10 times slower than multiplication.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A second drawback is that it will not break up clustered keys.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This technique works well in practice because many key sets are sufficiently random already, and the probability that a key set will be cyclical by a large prime number is small.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Algebraic coding is a variant of the division method of hashing which uses division by a polynomial modulo 2 instead of an integer to map n bits to m bits.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] If *Z*(*x*) is constructed to have t or fewer non-zero coefficients, then keys which share fewer than t bits are guaranteed to not collide.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Z is a function of k, t, and n (the last of which is a divisor of 2*k* − 1) and is constructed from the finite field GF(2*k*).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Define $P(x)=\prod _{j\in S}(x-\alpha ^{j})$ where α ∈*n* GF(2*k*) and where the coefficients of *P*(*x*) are computed in this field.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Since α2*j* is a root of *P*(*x*) whenever α*j* is a root, it follows that the coefficients *pi* of *P*(*x*) satisfy *p*2 *i* = *p*i, so they are all 0 or 1.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] If *R*(*x*) = *r**n*−1*x**n*−1 + ⋯ + *r*1*x* + *r*0 is any nonzero polynomial modulo 2 with at most t nonzero coefficients, then *R*(*x*) is not a multiple of *P*(*x*) modulo 2.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] If follows that the corresponding hash function will map keys with fewer than t bits in common to unique indices.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The usual outcome is that either n will get large, or t will get large, or both, for the scheme to be computationally feasible.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Therefore, it is more suited to hardware or microcode implementation.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Unique permutation hashing has a guaranteed best worst-case insertion time.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Standard multiplicative hashing uses the formula *h**a*(*K*) = ⌊(*aK* mod *W*) / (*W*/*M*)⌋, which produces a hash value in {0, …, *M* − 1}.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The value a is an appropriately chosen value that should be relatively prime to W; it should be large, and its binary representation a random mix of 1s and 0s.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] An important practical special case occurs when *W* = 2*w* and *M* = 2*m* are powers of 2 and w is the machine word size.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] and for fixed m and w this translates into a single integer multiplication and right-shift, making it one of the fastest hash functions to compute.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Multiplicative hashing is susceptible to a "common mistake" that leads to poor diffusion—higher-value input bits do not affect lower-value output bits.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A transmutation on the input which shifts the span of retained top bits down and XORs or ADDs them to the key before the multiplication step corrects for this.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Fibonacci hashing is a form of multiplicative hashing in which the multiplier is 2*w* / ϕ, where w is the machine word length and ϕ (phi) is the golden ratio (approximately 1.618).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A property of this multiplier is that it uniformly distributes over the table space, blocks of consecutive keys with respect to any block of bits in the key.
