[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Zobrist hashing was originally introduced as a means of compactly representing chess positions in computer game-playing programs.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A unique random number was assigned to represent each type of piece (six each for black and white) on each space of the board.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Thus a table of 64×12 such numbers is initialized at the start of the program.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The random numbers could be any length, but 64 bits was natural due to the 64 squares on the board.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A position was transcribed by cycling through the pieces in a position, indexing the corresponding random numbers (vacant spaces were not included in the calculation) and XORing them together (the starting value could be 0 (the identity value for XOR) or a random seed).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The resulting value was reduced by modulo, folding, or some other operation to produce a hash table index.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The original Zobrist hash was stored in the table as the representation of the position.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Later, the method was extended to hashing integers by representing each byte in each of 4 possible positions in the word by a unique 32-bit random number.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Thus, a table of 28×4 random numbers is constructed.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A 32-bit hashed integer is transcribed by successively indexing the table with the value of each byte of the plain text integer and XORing the loaded values together (again, the starting value can be the identity value or a random seed).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The natural extension to 64-bit integers is by use of a table of 28×8 64-bit random numbers.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This kind of function has some nice theoretical properties, one of which is called *3-tuple independence*, meaning that every 3-tuple of keys is equally likely to be mapped to any 3-tuple of hash values.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A hash function can be designed to exploit existing entropy in the keys.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] If the keys have leading or trailing zeros, or particular fields that are unused, always zero or some other constant, or generally vary little, then masking out only the volatile bits and hashing on those will provide a better and possibly faster hash function.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Selected divisors or multipliers in the division and multiplicative schemes may make more uniform hash functions if the keys are cyclic or have other redundancies.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] When the data values are long (or variable-length) character strings—such as personal names, web page addresses, or mail messages—their distribution is usually very uneven, with complicated dependencies.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] For example, text in any natural language has highly non-uniform distributions of characters, and character pairs, characteristic of the language.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] For such data, it is prudent to use a hash function that depends on all characters of the string—and depends on each character in a different way.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Simplistic hash functions may add the first and last *n* characters of a string along with the length, or form a word-size hash from the middle 4 characters of a string.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This saves iterating over the (potentially long) string, but hash functions that do not hash on all characters of a string can readily become linear due to redundancies, clustering, or other pathologies in the key set.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Such strategies may be effective as a custom hash function if the structure of the keys is such that either the middle, ends, or other fields are zero or some other invariant constant that does not differentiate the keys; then the invariant parts of the keys can be ignored.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The paradigmatic example of folding by characters is to add up the integer values of all the characters in the string.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A better idea is to multiply the hash total by a constant, typically a sizable prime number, before adding in the next character, ignoring overflow.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Using exclusive-or instead of addition is also a plausible alternative.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The final operation would be a modulo, mask, or other function to reduce the word value to an index the size of the table.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The weakness of this procedure is that information may cluster in the upper or lower bits of the bytes; this clustering will remain in the hashed result and cause more collisions than a proper randomizing hash.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] ASCII byte codes, for example, have an upper bit of 0, and printable strings do not use the last byte code or most of the first 32 byte codes, so the information, which uses the remaining byte codes, is clustered in the remaining bits in an unobvious manner.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The classic approach, dubbed the PJW hash based on the work of Peter J.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Weinberger at Bell Labs in the 1970s, was originally designed for hashing identifiers into compiler symbol tables as given in the "Dragon Book".
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This hash function offsets the bytes 4 bits before adding them together.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] When the quantity wraps, the high 4 bits are shifted out and if non-zero, xored back into the low byte of the cumulative quantity.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The result is a word-size hash code to which a modulo or other reducing operation can be applied to produce the final hash index.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Today, especially with the advent of 64-bit word sizes, much more efficient variable-length string hashing by word chunks is available.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The final word, which may have unoccupied byte positions, is filled with zeros or a specified randomizing value before being folded into the hash.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The accumulated hash code is reduced by a final modulo or other operation to yield an index into the table.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Analogous to the way an ASCII or EBCDIC character string representing a decimal number is converted to a numeric quantity for computing, a variable-length string can be converted as *x**k*−1a*k*−1 + *x**k*−2a*k*−2 + ⋯ + *x*1*a* + *x*0.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This is simply a polynomial in a radix *a* > 1 that takes the components (*x*0,*x*1,...,*x**k*−1) as the characters of the input string of length *k*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] It can be used directly as the hash code, or a hash function applied to it to map the potentially large value to the hash table size.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The value of *a* is usually a prime number large enough to hold the number of different characters in the character set of potential keys.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Radix conversion hashing of strings minimizes the number of collisions.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Available data sizes may restrict the maximum length of string that can be hashed with this method.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] For example, a 128-bit word will hash only a 26-character alphabetic string (ignoring case) with a radix of 29; a printable ASCII string is limited to 9 characters using radix 97 and a 64-bit word.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] However, alphabetic keys are usually of modest length, because keys must be stored in the hash table.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Numeric character strings are usually not a problem; 64 bits can count up to 1019, or 19 decimal digits with radix 10.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] In some applications, such as substring search, one can compute a hash function *h* for every *k*-character substring of a given *n*-character string by advancing a window of width *k* characters along the string, where *k* is a fixed integer, and *n* > *k*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The straightforward solution, which is to extract such a substring at every character position in the text and compute *h* separately, requires a number of operations proportional to *k*·*n*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] However, with the proper choice of *h*, one can use the technique of rolling hash to compute all those hashes with an effort proportional to *mk* + *n* where *m* is the number of occurrences of the substring.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The hash function used for the algorithm is usually the Rabin fingerprint, designed to avoid collisions in 8-bit character strings, but other suitable hash functions are also used.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Fuzzy hashing, also known as similarity hashing, is a technique for detecting data that is similar, but not exactly the same, as other data.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This is in contrast to cryptographic hash functions, which are designed to have significantly different hashes for even minor differences.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Fuzzy hashing has been used to identify malware and has potential for other applications, like data loss prevention and detecting multiple versions of code.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Perceptual hashing is the use of a fingerprinting algorithm that produces a snippet, hash, or fingerprint of various forms of multimedia.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] A perceptual hash is a type of locality-sensitive hash, which is analogous if features of the multimedia are similar.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This is in contrast to cryptographic hashing, which relies on the avalanche effect of a small change in input value creating a drastic change in output value.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Perceptual hash functions are widely used in finding cases of online copyright infringement as well as in digital forensics because of the ability to have a correlation between hashes so similar data can be found (for instance with a differing watermark).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] Worst case results for a hash function can be assessed two ways: theoretical and practical.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The theoretical worst case is the probability that all keys map to a single slot.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The practical worst case is the expected longest probe sequence (hash function + collision resolution method).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] This analysis considers uniform hashing, that is, any key will map to any particular slot with probability 1/*m*, a characteristic of universal hash functions.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] While Knuth worries about adversarial attack on real time systems, Gonnet has shown that the probability of such a case is "ridiculously small".
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] His representation was that the probability of *k* of *n* keys mapping to a single slot is α*k* / (*e*α *k*!), where *α* is the load factor, *n*/*m*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/hash-function] The term *hash* offers a natural analogy with its non-technical meaning (to chop up or make a mess out of something), given how hash functions scramble their input data to derive their output.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] A **quotient filter** is a space-efficient probabilistic data structure used to test whether an element is a member of a set (an approximate membership query filter, AMQ).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] A query will elicit a reply specifying either that the element is definitely not in the set or that the element is probably in the set.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The former result is definitive; *i.e.*, the test does not generate false negatives.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] But with the latter result there is some probability, ε, of the test returning "element is in the set" when in fact the element is not present in the set (*i.e.*, a false positive).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] There is a tradeoff between ε, the false positive rate, and storage size; increasing the filter's storage size reduces ε.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Other AMQ operations include "insert" and "optionally delete".
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The more elements are added to the set, the larger the probability of false positives.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] A typical application for quotient filters, and other AMQ filters, is to serve as a proxy for the keys in a database on disk.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] As keys are added to or removed from the database, the filter is updated to reflect this.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Any lookup will first consult the fast quotient filter, then look in the (presumably much slower) database only if the quotient filter reported the presence of the key.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] If the filter returns absence, the key is known not to be in the database without any disk accesses having been performed.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] A quotient filter has the usual AMQ operations of insert and query.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] In addition it can also be merged and re-sized without having to re-hash the original keys (thereby avoiding the need to access those keys from secondary storage).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] This property benefits certain kinds of log-structured merge-trees.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The compact hash table underlying a quotient filter was described by Cleary in 1984.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The first known reference to using the structure as an AMQ filter is by Pagh *et al.* in 2005.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] In 2009, Dillinger and Manolios optimized the structure's metadata, added in-place accommodation of more elements, and applied the structure to explicit-state model checking.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] In 2017, Pandey *et al.* described a version that uses hardware bit-manipulation instructions to improve performance, supports concurrent updates, and adds support for associating a variable-sized counter to each element.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The quotient filter is based on a kind of hash table in which entries contain only a portion of the key plus some additional meta-data bits.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] These bits are used to deal with the case when distinct keys happen to hash to the same table entry.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] By way of contrast, other types of hash tables that deal with such collisions by linking to overflow areas are not compact because the overhead due to linkage can exceed the storage used to store the key.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] In a quotient filter a hash function generates a *p*-bit fingerprint.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The *r* least significant bits is called the remainder while the *q* = *p* - *r* most significant bits is called the quotient, hence the name *quotienting* (coined by Knuth.) The hash table has 2q slots.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] For some key *d* which hashes to the fingerprint *dH*, let its quotient be *dQ* and the remainder be *dR*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] QF will try to store the remainder in slot dQ, which is known as the *canonical slot*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] However the canonical slot might already be occupied because multiple keys can hash to the same fingerprint—a *hard collision*—or because even when the keys' fingerprints are distinct they can have the same quotient—a *soft collision*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] If the canonical slot is occupied then the remainder is stored in some slot to the right.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] As described below, the insertion algorithm ensures that all fingerprints having the same quotient are stored in contiguous slots.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Such a set of fingerprints is defined as a *run*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Note that a run's first fingerprint might not occupy its canonical slot if the run has been forced right by some run to the left.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] However a run whose first fingerprint occupies its canonical slot indicates the start of a *cluster*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The initial run and all subsequent runs comprise the cluster, which terminates at an unoccupied slot or the start of another cluster.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The three additional bits are used to reconstruct a slot's fingerprint.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] is set when a slot is the canonical slot for some key stored (somewhere) in the filter (but not necessarily in this slot).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] is set when a slot is occupied but not by the first remainder in a run.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] is set when the remainder in a slot is not in its canonical slot.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] We can test if a quotient filter contains some key, d, as follows.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] We hash the key to produce its fingerprint, dH, which we then partition into its high-order q bits, dQ, which comprise its quotient, and its low-order r bits, dR, which comprise its remainder.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] That slot is empty if its three meta-data bits are false.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] In that case the filter does not contain the key.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] If the canonical slot is occupied then we must locate the quotient's run.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The set of slots that hold remainders belonging to the same quotient are stored contiguously and these comprise the quotient's run.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The first slot in the run might be the canonical slot but it is also possible that the entire run has been shifted to the right by the encroachment from the left of another run.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] To locate the quotient's run we must first locate the start of the cluster.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The cluster consists of a contiguous set of runs.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Starting with the quotient's canonical slot we can scan left to locate the start of the cluster, then scan right to locate the quotient's run.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] We scan left looking for a slot with *is_shifted* is false.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] This indicates the start of the cluster.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Then we scan right keeping a running count of the number of runs we must skip over.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Each slot to the left of the canonical slot having *is_occupied* **set** indicates another run to be skipped, so we increment the running count.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Each slot having *is_continuation* **clear** indicates the start of another run, thus the end of the previous run, so we decrement the running count.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] When the running count reaches zero, we are scanning the quotient's run.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] We can compare the remainder in each slot in the run with dR.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] If found, we report that the key is (probably) in the filter otherwise we report that the key is definitely not in the filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Take, for example, looking up element *e*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] We would compute *hash(e)*, partition it into its remainder, eR and its quotient eQ, which is 4.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Scanning left from slot 4 we encounter three *is_occupied* slots, at indexes 4, 2 and 1, indicating eQ's run is the 3rd run in the cluster.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The scan stops at slot 1, which we detect as the cluster's start because it is not empty and not shifted.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The start of a run is indicated by *is_continuation* being false.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The 1st run is found at index 1, the 2nd at 4 and the 3rd at 5.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] We compare the remainder held in each slot in the run that starts at index 5.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] There is only one slot in that run but, in our example, its remainder equals eR, indicating that *e* is indeed a member of the filter, with probability 1 - ε.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Insertion follows a path similar to lookup until we ascertain that the key is definitely not in the filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] At that point we insert the remainder in a slot in the current run, a slot chosen to keep the run in sorted order.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] We shift forward the remainders in any slots in the cluster at or after the chosen slot and update the slot bits.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The figure shows a quotient filter proceeding through a series of states as elements are added.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] In state 1 three elements have been added.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The slot each one occupies forms a one-slot run which is also a distinct cluster.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] In state 2 elements *c* and *d* have been added.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Element *c* has a quotient of 1, the same as *b*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] We assume bR < cR so cR is shifted into slot 2, and is marked as both a *continuation* and *shifted*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Since its canonical slot is in use, it is shifted into slot 3, and is marked as *shifted*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] In addition its canonical slot is marked as *occupied*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The runs for quotients 1 and 2 now comprise a cluster.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] We assume aR < bR so the remainders in slots 1 through 4 must be shifted.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Slot 2 receives bR and is marked as a *continuation* and *shifted*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Slot 5 receives eR and is marked as *shifted*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The runs for quotients 1, 2 and 4 now comprise a cluster, and the presence of those three runs in the cluster is indicated by having slots 1, 2 and 4 being marked as *occupied*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] This is important because lookups and inserts require locating the start and length of an entire cluster.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] If the hash function generates uniformly distributed fingerprints then the length of most runs is *O*(1) and it is highly likely that *all* runs have length *O*(log *m*) where *m* is the number of slots in the table.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Bender calculates the probability of a false positive (i.e. when the hash of two keys results in the same fingerprint) in terms of the hash table's remainder size and load factor.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Recall that a *p* bit fingerprint is partitioned into a *q* bit quotient, which determines the table size of *m* = 2q slots, and a *r* bit remainder.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The load factor $\alpha$ is the proportion of occupied slots *n* to total slots *m*: $\alpha =n/m$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Then, for a good hash function, $1-e^{-\alpha /2^{r}}\leq 2^{-r}$ is approximately the probability of a hard collision.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Pandey's version of the quotient filter requires less space than a comparable Bloom filter when the target false-positive rate is less than 1/64.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Quotient filters are AMQs and, as such, provide many of the same benefits as Bloom filters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] A large database, such as Webtable may be composed of smaller sub-tables each of which has an associated filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Each query is distributed concurrently to all sub-tables.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] If a sub-table does not contain the requested element, its filter can quickly complete the request without incurring any I/O.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Quotient filters offer two benefits in some applications.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] A few duplicates can be tolerated efficiently and can be deleted.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The space used by quotient filters is comparable to that of Bloom filters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] However quotient filters can be efficiently merged within memory without having to re-insert the original keys.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] This is particularly important in some log structured storage systems that use the log-structured merge-tree or LSM-tree.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The LSM-tree is actually a collection of trees but which is treated as a single key-value store.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] One variation of the LSM-Tree is the Sorted Array Merge Tree or SAMT.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] In this variation, a SAMT's component trees are called Wanna-B-trees.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Each Wanna-*B*-tree has an associated quotient filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] A query on the SAMT is directed at only select Wanna-*B*-trees as evidenced by their quotient filters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] The storage system in its normal operation compacts the SAMT's Wanna-*B*-trees, merging smaller Wanna-*B*-trees into larger ones and merging their quotient filters.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] An essential property of quotient filters is that they can be efficiently merged without having to re-insert the original keys.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Given that for large data sets the Wanna-*B*-trees may not be in memory, accessing them to retrieve the original keys would incur many I/Os.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] By construction the values in a quotient filter are stored in sorted order.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Each run is associated with a specific quotient value, which provides the most significant portion of the fingerprint, the runs are stored in order and each slot in the run provides the least significant portion of the fingerprint.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] So, by working from left to right, one can reconstruct all the fingerprints and the resulting list of integers will be in sorted order.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Merging two quotient filters is then a simple matter of converting each quotient filter into such a list, merging the two lists and using it to populate a new larger quotient filter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/quotient-filter] Similarly, we can halve or double the size of a quotient filter without rehashing the keys since the fingerprints can be recomputed using just the quotients and remainders.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] In computer science, **streaming algorithms** process input data streams as a sequence of items, typically making just one pass (or a few passes) through the data.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] These algorithms are designed to operate with limited memory, generally logarithmic in the size of the stream and/or in the maximum value in the stream, and may also have limited processing time per item.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] As a result of these constraints, streaming algorithms often produce approximate answers based on a summary or "sketch" of the data stream.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Though streaming algorithms had already been studied by Munro and Paterson as early as 1978, as well as Philippe Flajolet and G.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Nigel Martin in 1982/83, the field of streaming algorithms was first formalized and popularized in a 1996 paper by Noga Alon, Yossi Matias, and Mario Szegedy.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Semi-streaming algorithms were introduced in 2005 as a relaxation of streaming algorithms for graphs, in which the space allowed is linear in the number of vertices *n*, but only logarithmic in the number of edges *m*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] This relaxation is still meaningful for dense graphs, and can solve interesting problems (such as connectivity) that are insoluble in $o(n)$ space.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] In the data stream model, some or all of the input is represented as a finite sequence of integers (from some finite domain) which is generally not available for random access, but instead arrives one at a time in a "stream".
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] If the stream has length *n* and the domain has size *m*, algorithms are generally constrained to use space that is logarithmic in *m* and *n*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] They can generally make only some small constant number of passes over the stream, sometimes just one.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Much of the streaming literature is concerned with computing statistics on frequency distributions that are too large to be stored.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] For this class of problems, there is a vector $\mathbf {a} =(a_{1},\dots ,a_{n})$ (initialized to the zero vector $\mathbf {0}$ ) that has updates presented to it in a stream.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] The goal of these algorithms is to compute functions of $\mathbf {a}$ using considerably less space than it would take to represent $\mathbf {a}$ precisely.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] There are two common models for updating such streams, called the "cash register" and "turnstile" models.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] In the cash register model, each update is of the form $\langle i,c\rangle$ , so that $a_{i}$ is incremented by some positive integer c .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] A notable special case is when $c=1$ (only unit insertions are permitted).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] In the turnstile model, each update is of the form $\langle i,c\rangle$ , so that $a_{i}$ is incremented by some (possibly negative) integer c .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] In the "strict turnstile" model, no $a_{i}$ at any time may be less than zero.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Several papers also consider the "sliding window" model.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] In this model, the function of interest is computing over a fixed-size window in the stream.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] As the stream progresses, items from the end of the window are removed from consideration while new items from the stream take their place.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Besides the above frequency-based problems, some other types of problems have also been studied.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Many graph problems are solved in the setting where the adjacency matrix or the adjacency list of the graph is streamed in some unknown order.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] There are also some problems that are very dependent on the order of the stream (i.e., asymmetric functions), such as counting the number of inversions in a stream and finding the longest increasing subsequence.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] These algorithms have many similarities with online algorithms since they both require decisions to be made before all data are available, but they are not identical.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Data stream algorithms only have limited memory available but they may be able to defer action until a group of points arrive, while online algorithms are required to take action as soon as each point arrives.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] If the algorithm is an approximation algorithm then the accuracy of the answer is another key factor.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] The accuracy is often stated as an $(\epsilon ,\delta )$ approximation meaning that the algorithm achieves an error of less than $\epsilon$ with probability $1-\delta$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Streaming algorithms have several applications in networking such as monitoring network links for elephant flows, counting the number of distinct flows, estimating the distribution of flow sizes, and so on.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] They also have applications in databases, such as estimating the size of a join .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] The kth frequency moment of a set of frequencies $\mathbf {a}$ is defined as $F_{k}(\mathbf {a} )=\sum _{i=1}^{n}a_{i}^{k}$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] The first moment $F_{1}$ is simply the sum of the frequencies (i.e., the total count).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] The second moment $F_{2}$ is useful for computing statistical properties of the data, such as the Gini coefficient of variation. $F_{\infty }$ is defined as the frequency of the most frequent items.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] The seminal paper of Alon, Matias, and Szegedy dealt with the problem of estimating the frequency moments.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] A direct approach to find the frequency moments requires to maintain a register mi for all distinct elements *a**i* ∈ (1,2,3,4,...,*N*) which requires at least memory of order $\Omega (N)$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] But we have space limitations and require an algorithm that computes in much lower memory.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] This can be achieved by using approximations instead of exact values.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] An algorithm that computes an (*ε,δ*)approximation of Fk, where F'k is the (*ε,δ*)- approximated value of Fk.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Where *ε* is the approximation parameter and *δ* is the confidence parameter.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Flajolet et al. in introduced a probabilistic method of counting which was inspired from a paper by Robert Morris.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Morris in his paper says that if the requirement of accuracy is dropped, a counter *n* can be replaced by a counter log *n* which can be stored in log log *n* bits.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Flajolet et al. in improved this method by using a hash function h which is assumed to uniformly distribute the element in the hash space (a binary string of length L).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Let $\rho (y)$ represents the position of least significant 1-bit in the binary representation of yi with a suitable convention for $\rho (0)$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Let *A* be the sequence of data stream of length *M* whose cardinality need to be determined.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] hash space where the ρ(*hashedvalues*) are recorded.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] The below algorithm then determines approximate cardinality of *A*.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] If there are *N* distinct elements in a data stream.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] The previous algorithm describes the first attempt to approximate *F*0 in the data stream by Flajolet and Martin.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Their algorithm picks a random hash function which they assume to uniformly distribute the hash values in hash space.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Bar-Yossef et al. in introduced k-minimum value algorithm for determining number of distinct elements in data stream.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] They used a similar hash function *h* which can be normalized to [0,1] as $h:[m]\rightarrow [0,1]$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] But they fixed a limit *t* to number of values in hash space.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] The value of *t* is assumed of the order $O\left({\dfrac {1}{\varepsilon _{2}}}\right)$ (i.e. less approximation-value *ε* requires more *t*).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] KMV algorithm keeps only *t*-smallest hash values in the hash space.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] After all the *m* values of stream have arrived, $\upsilon =\mathrm {Max} (h(a_{i}))$ is used to calculate $F'_{0}={\dfrac {t}{\upsilon }}$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] That is, in a close-to uniform hash space, they expect at-least *t* elements to be less than $O\left({\dfrac {t}{F_{0}}}\right)$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] KMV algorithm can be implemented in $O\left(\left({\dfrac {1}{\varepsilon _{2}}}\right)\cdot \log(m)\right)$ memory bits space.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Each hash value requires space of order $O(\log(m))$ memory bits.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] There are hash values of the order $O\left({\dfrac {1}{\varepsilon _{2}}}\right)$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] The access time can be reduced if we store the *t* hash values in a binary tree.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Thus the time complexity will be reduced to $O\left(\log \left({\dfrac {1}{\varepsilon }}\right)\cdot \log(m)\right)$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Alon et al. estimates Fk by defining random variables that can be computed within given space and time.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] The expected value of random variables gives the approximate value of Fk.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Assume length of sequence *m* is known in advance.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Algorithm takes *S*2 random variable $Y_{1},Y_{2},...,Y_{S2}$ and outputs the median Y .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Where Yi is the average of Xij where 1 ≤ *j* ≤ *S*1.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Now calculate expectation of random variable *E*(*X*).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] From the algorithm to calculate Fk discussed above, we can see that each random variable X stores value of ap and r.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] So, to compute X we need to maintain only log(*n*) bits for storing ap and log(*n*) bits for storing r.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Total number of random variable X will be the ⁠ $S_{1}*S_{2}$ ⁠.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] The previous algorithm calculates $F_{2}$ in order of $O({\sqrt {n}}(\log m+\log n))$ memory bits.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Alon et al. in simplified this algorithm using four-wise independent random variable with values mapped to $\{-1,1\}$ .
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] In the data stream model, the **frequent elements problem** is to output a set of elements that constitute more than some fixed fraction of the stream.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] A special case is the **majority problem**, which is to determine whether or not any value constitutes a majority of the stream.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] More formally, fix some positive constant *c* > 1, let the length of the stream be *m*, and let *f**i* denote the frequency of value *i* in the stream.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] The frequent elements problem is to output the set { *i* | *f**i* > m/c }.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Detecting events in data streams is often done using a heavy hitters algorithm as listed above: the most frequent items and their frequency are determined using one of these algorithms, then the largest increase over the previous time point is reported as trend.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] This approach can be refined by using exponentially weighted moving averages and variance for normalization.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Counting the number of distinct elements in a stream (sometimes called the *F*0 moment) is another problem that has been well studied.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] The first algorithm for it was proposed by Flajolet and Martin.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] In 2010, Daniel Kane, Jelani Nelson and David Woodruff found an asymptotically optimal algorithm for this problem.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] It uses *O*(*ε*2 + log *d*) space, with *O*(1) worst-case update and reporting times, as well as universal hash functions and a r-wise independent hash family where *r* = Ω(log(1/*ε*) / log log(1/*ε*)).
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Learn a model (e.g. a classifier) by a single pass over a training set.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] Lower bounds have been computed for many of the data streaming problems that have been studied.
[src:counting-bloom-filter/streaming-algorithm] By far, the most common technique for computing these lower bounds has been using communication complexity.
